<subSubSection id="AFE980F5460032B2197537F0042F9774" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="EBD171139F0249AE6B4E3BE87D85B0CF" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9DF764783A5905CDB50FD2AE1515C785" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">
A new record for the Greek flora (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="146A09B54E283250885F30254682C4F5" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F7677634" captionText="Figure 14. Saponaria stranjensis from Nomos Evrou (photo: P. Doumas)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/640548" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">14</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="BD2EB71ABE9713F45381CC1B1ADE8C29" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Saponaria" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saponaria stranjensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="9595989309FD65236FB2C0B19C61B0A0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Saponaria stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in Bulgaria and European Turkey (
<bibRefCitation id="0E25604E14B3CF5BF34BF554DEDFA15F" author="Petrova, A." journalOrPublisher="Phytologia Balcanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="293 - 311" refId="B7669158" refString="Petrova, A., Vladimirov, V., 2010. Balkan endemics in the Bulgarian flora. Phytologia Balcanica 16 (2): 293 - 311" title="Balkan endemics in the Bulgarian flora" volume="16" year="2010">Petrova and Vladimirov 2010</bibRefCitation>
). The two localities of Nomos Evrou extend the 
<normalizedToken id="859F888FCF55D6F8FB00051706B9918C" originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
known distribution to the south. Its closest taxonomic relative, 
<taxonomicName id="B76F0A8A5A7818CF85BA8E2B04DAF4DB" genus="S." lsidName="S. intermedia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis id="CD30737D00BE77DABF59178445F5AA5B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Simmler, differs by usually having stems up to 50 cm (longer as a rule in 
<taxonomicName id="68EB5CBCC9207B439565AB614ED4B897" genus="S." lsidName="S. stranjensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="B276A52130854738C0B035F644445FA8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and calyx with abundant eglandular hairs, rarely with a few short, glandular hairs, opposite to the calyx with abundant long and short glandular hairs in 
<taxonomicName id="34511835E8511D005D68DCF93D918049" genus="S." lsidName="S. stranjensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="2EDC8F1EC6C5EC2C2B7FD428D72E88F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although stem length may be a variable character and related to environmental conditions, our two randomly collected Greek specimens measure ca. 52 and 56 cm, respectively. Still, some authors consider those two taxa at subspecific rank rather than independent species (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="E51233EB1706914FD299F7811500BDA4" author="Jalas, J." journalOrPublisher="Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, New York, Melbourne" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7668825" refString="Jalas, J., Suominen, J., 1988. Atlas Florae Europaeae III. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, New York, Melbourne" title="Atlas Florae Europaeae III" year="1988">Jalas and Suominen 1988</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="CA513A5B336131CF64159C53DC8212E3" author="Chater, A. O." journalOrPublisher="Cambridge University Press, Cambridge" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7667974" refString="Chater, A. O., 1993. Flora Europaea Vol. 1 (2nd edition). Cambridge University Press, Cambridge" title="Flora Europaea Vol. 1 (2 nd edition)" year="1993">Chater 1993</bibRefCitation>
), thus disagreeing with 
<bibRefCitation id="72D74B555A6C27346C5A06B1E1AA460A" author="Mayer, E." journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Croatica" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="239 - 244" refId="B7668940" refString="Mayer, E., 1976. Zur Kenntnis des Saponaria sicula -Komplexes auf der Balkanhalbinsel. Acta Botanica Croatica 35: 239 - 244" title="Zur Kenntnis des Saponaria sicula - Komplexes auf der Balkanhalbinsel" volume="35" year="1976">Mayer (1976)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A6710970C954470FA00DFBA5F4FA0CCC" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">
In Greece, the two species have a clearly different distribution range: 
<taxonomicName id="D34723AF1293334844D48E826FEDABB1" genus="S." lsidName="S. intermedia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis id="3F29AD8D9560EEF305546EDFEAFA7677" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
extends at the northern parts of Pindos Mountain chain and again found around Mt. Vourinos, at the NW parts of Greece (
<bibRefCitation id="0625E2BBB55D3D5CCE3F7067C848A95B" author="Phitos, D." journalOrPublisher="Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669176" refString="Phitos, D., 1997. Flora Hellenica 1. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" title="Flora Hellenica 1" year="1997">Phitos 1997</bibRefCitation>
), where it usually grows on serpentine. 
<taxonomicName id="E94C6499671A942FACCED72E4FDA27F9" genus="S." lsidName="S. stranjensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="2714083BF4412047531F5159BE347770" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs ca. 400 km to the east, near the small town of Soufli, close to the Greek-Turkish border. 
<normalizedToken id="1026F1A260593C4472E3FDC4AF49810C" originalValue="Τhe">Τhe</normalizedToken>
two species also present a different altitudinal range in Greece: 
<taxonomicName id="7AC88AF0D5043C3E017C5A5B4D0F951B" genus="S." lsidName="S. intermedia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis id="55EBDCF79EF6016D9E6B95722212A668" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grows at 850-1800 m a.s.l., whereas 
<taxonomicName id="507972C3D7BF0A72A852BBDDCBBBF0E8" genus="S." lsidName="S. stranjensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="022142383C963296D7230538E5DE9384" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found at 30-260 m a.s.l. In Bulgaria, the latter species has been recorded from 300 up to 500 m a.s.l. (
<bibRefCitation id="8B06EB189E7CF154949178F267D08071" author="Peev, D." journalOrPublisher="Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669119" refString="Peev, D., Petrova, A., Anchev, M., Temniskova, D., Denchev, C. M., Ganeva, A., Gussev, C., Vladimirov, V., 2015. Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi. Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" title="Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi" year="2015">Peev et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The two Greek localities were found ca. 1.5 and 7.5 km west of the Greek-Turkish border, respectively (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="87C9179AB8082F945E4F968B0F74BB05" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7677570" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution map of Centaurea marmorea, Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala, Hesperis matronalis subsp. matronalis and Saponaria stranjensis in Greece." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/656686" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C30ECA72C0B13970C29F14AACB8C57AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">
<taxonomicName id="88B201DD3A9FB0677BD6F7D0874066B3" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Saponaria" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saponaria stranjensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="4ED733096E7FE28946CA7D58D6B409EF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Saponaria stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been assessed as Vulnerable in Bulgaria (
<bibRefCitation id="88F9E2CCA82620895888C73910C559BD" author="Petrova, A." journalOrPublisher="Phytologia Balcanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="63 - 94" refId="B7669149" refString="Petrova, A., Vladimirov, V., 2009. Red list of Bulgarian vascular plants. Phytologia Balcanica 15 (1): 63 - 94" title="Red list of Bulgarian vascular plants" volume="15" year="2009">Petrova and Vladimirov 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="98D5096861B1B03BC7DC05EEDAE85DC3" author="Peev, D." journalOrPublisher="Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669119" refString="Peev, D., Petrova, A., Anchev, M., Temniskova, D., Denchev, C. M., Ganeva, A., Gussev, C., Vladimirov, V., 2015. Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi. Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" title="Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi" year="2015">Peev et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
) and is being protected by the National Biodiversity Act. Extinction has been observed in at least one previously known population in that country (
<bibRefCitation id="230359372390B2A9189412FD132BFC26" author="Peev, D." journalOrPublisher="Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669119" refString="Peev, D., Petrova, A., Anchev, M., Temniskova, D., Denchev, C. M., Ganeva, A., Gussev, C., Vladimirov, V., 2015. Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi. Academy of Sciences &amp; Ministry of Environment and Water, Sofia" title="Red Data Book of the Republic of Bulgaria 1. Plants and fungi" year="2015">Peev et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). In Greece, 
<taxonomicName id="F620E85E3C7A5259506F02D12C65DA11" genus="S." lsidName="S. stranjensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="stranjensis">
<emphasis id="8621C7D4DD1AF8B38429638B755214EB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">S. stranjensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very local: its populations are geographically restricted and consist of a few dozens of mature plants only. We presume that the Greek populations are threatened, but a proper assessment according to the IUCN Categories and Criteria is still pending. The two Greek localities form a noteworthy extension of the nearest Bulgarian population: ca. 25 km to the SE.
</paragraph>
